Implement the `handle_call/3` GenServer callback for `LRUCacheSharded.Shard`.

This callback serialises all writes for a single shard. It has two clauses.

**`{:touch, key}`** — refreshes the recency of an existing key (called after a
read hit). Look the key up in the shard's data table. If it is present as
`{key, {value, old_ts}}`, obtain a fresh timestamp via `next_counter/1`, delete
the old `old_ts` entry from the order table, insert the new `{new_ts, key}` entry
into the order table, and re-insert `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into the data table
(keeping the same value). If the key is absent, do nothing. In both cases reply
`:ok` with the (possibly updated) state.

**`{:put, key, value}`** — inserts or updates a key. Look the key up in the data
table:

* If it already exists (`{key, {_old, old_ts}}`), it is an update: get a fresh
  timestamp with `next_counter/1`, delete the stale `old_ts` from the order
  table, insert `{new_ts, key}` into the order table, and write
  `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into the data table.
* If it is absent, it is a fresh insert: first make room by calling
  `maybe_evict/1` (which drops the least-recently-used entry when the shard is at
  capacity), then get a fresh timestamp with `next_counter/1`, insert
  `{new_ts, key}` into the order table, and write `{key, {value, new_ts}}` into
  the data table.

Reply `:ok` with the updated state.

`next_counter/1` returns `{new_ts, new_state}`, so thread the state through it in
every branch. Eviction must remain strictly per-shard.

